{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586684"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15088"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.28,0.24,0.14,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67911"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7776"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5323"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"9882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67911"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn bilateral ureteric or high-pressure bladder outlet obstruction, vasoactive substances including prostaglandins and nitric oxide accumulate after 90 minutes. These substances significantly affect renal tubular function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect on renal tubular function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced sodium reabsorption","Increased urine acidification","Increased potassium secretion","Enhanced glucose reabsorption","Increased calcium reabsorption"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn ureteric obstruction, the accumulation of prostaglandins and nitric oxide leads to several changes in tubular function. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced sodium reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to prostaglandin-mediated inhibition of sodium-potassium ATPase and sodium channels in the renal tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased urine acidification\u003C/strong\u003E - Acidification is actually reduced due to impaired hydrogen ion secretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased potassium secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Potassium handling is impaired in ureteric obstruction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced glucose reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose transport is reduced rather than enhanced\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased calcium reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium reabsorption is typically impaired in this condition\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes occur due to the direct effects of accumulated prostaglandins and nitric oxide on various transport mechanisms in the renal tubules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bilateral ureteric obstruction causes reduced sodium reabsorption due to accumulation of prostaglandins and nitric oxide","Prostaglandins inhibit sodium-potassium ATPase and sodium channels in the renal tubules","Ureteric obstruction impairs multiple tubular functions including acidification, potassium handling, and glucose transport"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53376"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53376"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:38:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:39:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7776"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67911"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","sy